{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e1d94f3-f341-4421-be7f-25fe33bf82e1","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 — great. Here's the modern recommended approach:\n\n**Constructor injection for `TestContext`** (MSTest v3+), combined with `[TestInitialize]` for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // asynchronous setup here (e.g., DB seeding, HTTP clients)\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Using injected TestContext\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`TestContext`**: Inject via constructor parameter (preferred in v3+). The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property still works but constructor injection is cleaner.\n- **Sync init**: Use the constructor for synchronous per-test setup.\n- **Async init**: Use `[TestInitialize] public async Task ...()` — constructors can't be async, so this is the only option for async per-test setup.\n- **Class-level** (once per class): Use `[ClassInitialize] public static async Task Init(TestContext ctx)` for expensive one-time async setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"116a2117-7412-4f71-9341-0f2de4a9c2dc","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"1BC4:F3EF4:22FF125:26A8356:6A03D730"},"id":"4c2ad5ad-f2bf-4d31-a5a4-72ccb5606699","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:43:20.875Z","parentId":"d54836a2-2036-420b-a9b3-ced45200dcfe"}
